Thanks for confirming! MPLAB X IDE v4.70 is a bit older, but still capable of working with PIC32 and lwIP. Here‚Äôs a full step-by-step tailored for **MPLAB X v4.70** with **lwIP and HTTP server on PIC32**.

---

## ‚úÖ Step-by-Step for MPLAB X v4.70 + PIC32 + lwIP Web Server

---

### üìÅ 1. Project Structure

Inside your MPLAB project, create folders like this:
```
MyProject/
‚îÇ
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ main.c               ‚Üê System init + lwIP + web server start
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ fsdata.c             ‚Üê Contains web page content as C array
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ fsdata.h             ‚Üê Declares `fsdata_file` struct
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ index.html           ‚Üê (Optional reference)
‚îÇ
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ lwip/                ‚Üê Add lwIP source files
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ core/
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ netif/
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ include/
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ apps/httpd/
‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ port/            ‚Üê Add Ethernet HAL: `ethernetif.c`, `ethernetif.h`
```

---

### üîß 2. Project Configuration in MPLAB X v4.70

#### a. Add source files:
Right-click on **Source Files ‚Üí Add Existing Items**:
- Add `main.c`, `fsdata.c`, and `fsdata.h`

#### b. Add include directories:
Right-click project ‚Üí **Properties ‚Üí XC32 ‚Üí Compiler ‚Üí Include Directories**:
```
../lwip/include
../lwip/core
../lwip/netif
../lwip/apps/httpd
../lwip/port
```

#### c. Modify `lwipopts.h`:
Make sure these are set:
```c
#define LWIP_HTTPD               1
#define HTTPD_USE_CUSTOM_FSDATA 1
#define NO_SYS                   1
#define LWIP_SOCKET              0
#define LWIP_NETCONN             0
```

---

### üß† 3. Configure IP Address (Static)

In your `main.c`, set the IP manually:
```c
ip4_addr_t ipaddr, netmask, gw;
IP4_ADDR(&ipaddr, 192,168,1,123);   // Static IP
IP4_ADDR(&netmask, 255,255,255,0);
IP4_ADDR(&gw, 192,168,1,1);         // Your router
```

You‚Äôll see this IP in your browser after programming.

---

### üîå 4. Connect Hardware

- Connect Ethernet cable to PIC32‚Äôs PHY (LAN8720/ENC28J60)
- Use a PICKit3/4 or ICD4 to flash
- Open UART terminal at 115200 to see debug output
- Supply 3.3V power

---

### ‚ñ∂Ô∏è 5. Build & Program

- Click **Clean and Build** in MPLAB X
- Click **Make and Program Device**
- Monitor UART for messages like:
  ```
  IP Address: 192.168.1.123
  HTTP Server started...
  ```

---

### üåê 6. Access from Web Browser

- Ensure your PC is on same network (e.g. 192.168.1.x)
- Open browser and go to:
  ```
  http://192.168.1.123
  ```

You should see the HTML content:
> Hello from PIC32! This is a test page served by the PIC32 using lwIP.

---

### üß∞ Optional: Use DHCP Instead of Static

In `main.c`, replace static IP lines with:
```c
dhcp_start(&netif);
```
Ensure:
```c
#define LWIP_DHCP 1
```

