Perfect ‚Äî you're very close now! After creating `fsdata.c`, `fsdata.h`, and your project files, here‚Äôs how to **build, program, and run** the lwIP web server on your **PIC32** using **MPLAB X v4.70**.

---

## ‚úÖ Final Steps: How to Run the Web Server on PIC32

---

### üõ†Ô∏è 1. Add Files to Your Project

In **MPLAB X v4.70**:

1. Right-click **Source Files** ‚Üí Add:
   - `main.c`
   - `fsdata.c`
2. Right-click **Header Files** ‚Üí Add:
   - `fsdata.h`
3. Make sure all `lwIP` source files are included:
   - `lwip/core`
   - `lwip/netif`
   - `lwip/apps/httpd`
   - `port` files: `ethernetif.c`, `ethernetif.h`

---

### ‚öôÔ∏è 2. Check Compiler and Linker Settings

#### ‚û§ Include Paths:
Go to **Project Properties** ‚Üí `XC32 Compiler ‚Üí Include directories`:
```
../lwip/include
../lwip/core
../lwip/netif
../lwip/apps/httpd
../lwip/port
```

#### ‚û§ Preprocessor Definitions:
Also define in compiler settings:
```c
LWIP_HTTPD=1
HTTPD_USE_CUSTOM_FSDATA=1
NO_SYS=1
```

If using static IP, no need for RTOS or `tcpip_thread`.

---

### üß† 3. Static IP Configuration (main.c)

Inside your `main.c`:
```c
ip4_addr_t ipaddr, netmask, gw;

// Use an IP that matches your network
IP4_ADDR(&ipaddr, 192,168,1,123);
IP4_ADDR(&netmask, 255,255,255,0);
IP4_ADDR(&gw, 192,168,1,1);

netif_add(&netif, &ipaddr, &netmask, &gw, NULL, ethernetif_init, ethernet_input);
netif_set_default(&netif);
netif_set_up(&netif);

httpd_init();  // Start HTTP Server
```

---

### üîå 4. Hardware Setup

Make sure:

| Component | Status |
|----------|--------|
| Ethernet PHY | Connected via RMII (e.g., LAN8720 or ENC28J60) |
| RJ45 Jack | Plugged into your router |
| MCU Power | 3.3V stable |
| UART Debug | Optional (for IP printout) |

---

### üß™ 5. Build and Flash

In MPLAB:
- Click **Clean and Build Project**
- Click **Make and Program Device**
- Use your PICkit3/4 or ICD to flash the PIC32

---

### üì° 6. Connect to the Web Page

Once programmed:

1. Connect your PC to the **same network/router** as the PIC32
2. Open a browser and go to:
   ```
   http://192.168.1.123
   ```

You should see:

> **Hello from PIC32!**  
> (or whatever was in your `index.html`)

‚úÖ If you see the page ‚Äî your lwIP HTTP server is running on your microcontroller!

---

### üîç Optional Debug (UART)

If you want to print IP for confirmation:
```c
#include <stdio.h>
printf("IP Address: %s\n", ip4addr_ntoa(&ipaddr));
```

